summary.seg: This manuscript, probably copied in the 10th or 11th century, contains various orations, epistles, carmina by the Patriarch of Constantinople, Gregory of Nazianzus. The manuscript was quite a high-quality production, with a Pyle (f. 1r) decorated with a mosaic motif, elegantly written with its initials and original marginal annotations; nevertheless it has suffered damage due to use and time and the first and last folios are much damaged. In spite of the importance of its contents, the spine bears an erroneous title.

The manuscript is divided into two sections corresponding to two mises-en-page. The first section (ff. 1r-326r) is written in two columns and contains the texts of Gregory of Nazianzus. The second (ff. 326v-357v) is written in a single column by the same hand as the first section and continues the text without interruption. Indeed, this section does not begin with a new quire but on the verso of the last folio in two columns (quire 41). This section contains additional commentary texts to Gregory of Nazianzus. On the last folio (ff. 357r-357v) two texts were added after the production of the manuscript, in a strongly contracted script, now nearly illegible.
Previously owned by the Greek monastery of Pantokratoros on Mount Athos, the manuscript B.9.13 was bought by the classical scholar Richard Bentley and bequeathed to Trinity College after his death.

Theologica III vel De filio I
msItem.rubric: f. 1r Τοῦ ἐν ἁγίοις πατρὸς ἡμῶν Γρηγορίου ἀρχιεπισκόπου Κωνσταντινουπόλεως τοῦ θεολόγου· περὶ υἰοῦ λόγος αʹ

support.material: ff. 1r-357v: Parchment, medium thickness, arranged flesh-to-flesh and hair-to-hair with hair outermost (HFFH).

supportDesc.foliation: [i] + 1-262, 262a, 263-357 + [ii]. Modern foliation in brown ink in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right corner.
supportDesc.collation:
The manuscript consists of 44 quires:
Quires 1-448 ff. 1r-351v
Quire 456 ff. 352r-357v
Quire signature in Greek numerals in light brown ink, sometimes faded, on the first folio recto and the last folio verso of the quires, lower margin, from f. 8v (αʹ) to f. 357v (μεʹ), missing on ff. 56v, 104v, 153r, 168v, 185r and 216v.
Five quire signatures in Greek numerals from a different sequence, but consistent with the main one, remain on the upper right-hand corner of ff. 17r (γʹ), 25r (δʹ), 33r (εʹ), 233r (λʹ) and 257r (λγʹ).

condition.p: In good condition. The initial and final folios are subject to greater wear and tear; a patch covers three lines on f. 1v, rewritten; the last folio verso is illegible. f. 1 has a torn seam, ff. 1-5 have some holes between the columns of text, repaired in 2020. The outer margin of f. 51 is partially cut, the inner margin of f. 54 is torn, f. 269 has a tear, f. 142 an eraser smear. The margins of ff. 52, 106, 117, 202, 211, 217, 255, 280, 318, 319 are cut at the line of justification.

layoutDesc.layout:
ff. 1r-326r: written space 215 150
27 lines per column. Pricked in the outer margins. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 66C2f .

ff. 326v-357v: written space 215 150
27 lines per page. Pricking does not survive Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, ff. 326-335 (quires 41-42) type Leroy 66C2f (as ff. ff. 1-326); joint ff. 336 and 343 (outermost folio of quire 43) type Leroy C 02C1a ; ff. 337-342 and 344-357 type Leroy 00C1 .

handNote.p: The manuscript is written in a minuscule script, upright or slanting slightly to the right, in dark brown ink, hanging from the ruling line. There is only moderate variation in letter size.
Headings are written in Alexandrine majuscule style. Scholia and annotations are written in majuscule with a large use of suprescript abbreviations.
Syllabic abbreviations are in use only for nomina sacra. Breathings are round and mute iota is occasionally adscript.
Punctuation includes the middle and upper point and full stop.
The last two texts on ff. 357r-357v are written in a mixed minuscule script, slanting to the right, in light brown ink, with extensive use of contractions and abbreviations.

decoDesc.decoNote: A pyle on f. 1r, partially lost, with mosaic pattern in blue, purple, green, orange tiles and spiral leaves on corners.
Major initial outlined in red and green on f. 1r.
Small initials in red ink from f. 14r.

additions.p: f. 1r: the name Ἀρσενίου on the lower margin.
Possession note on f. 1r (partially lost) and f. 3r: θεολόγος μονῆς παντοκράτορος χριστοῦ.
f. 321r: a name repeated three times in the lower margin Γαβριήλ
f. 357r: an owernship note on th upper margin: Τοῦτο τὸ βιβλίον ἔστιν κτῆμα τοῦ Κονσταντίνου [unclear] τοῦ Γαρδικίου.

binding.p: Full tanned calfskin, tightback. Spine with bands tooled in gold and a red leather label with title: Chrysostomi Homilae in Genesim. Τhe author name (Γρ θεολ) is present on the headband.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied in the 10th or 11th century.
history.provenance: The manuscript comes from the Monastery of the Pantokrator Monē Pantokratoros (Athos, Greece) on Mount Athos (see notes on ff. 1r, 3r): from the possession notes is not clear whether Θεολόγος refers to Gregorius of Nazianzus or a monk of the monastery. The possession note of Constantinos of Gardikion on f. 357r is in all likelihood earlier. The manuscript was brought from Mount Athos by Richard Bentley.
history.acquisition: Bequeathed to Trinity College Library by Bentley, Richard, 1662-1742 Richard Bentley (1662-1742) , Master of the College.

recordHist.source: Description (2020) draws on M.R. James, The Western Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College, Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1900), vol. 1, pp. 275-277.

availability.p: Visitors to Trinity College who wish to consult Special Collections material are required to apply to the Library in advance of their visit. For information on eligibility and admission procedures see: Trinity College: Information for Readers.
